.TH MZDECO 1 2000-1月 "peak_alignment" "peak_alignment"
.SH NAME
peak_alignment \- Do COW peak alignment and export peaktable
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fIpeak_alignment(\fBsamples\fR as any, 
\fBmzdiff\fR as double = 0.025, 
\fBrt_win\fR as double = 30, 
\fBri_win\fR as double = 10, 
\fBnorm\fR as boolean = FALSE, 
\fBri_alignment\fR as boolean = FALSE, 
\fBmax_intensity_ion\fR as boolean = FALSE, 
\fBnative_alignment\fR as boolean = FALSE, 
\fBaggregate\fR as <integer> Aggregates = [Sum], 
\fBtolerance_mode\fR as <integer> MassToleranceType = [Da], 
\fBmethod\fR as <integer> AlignmentMethod = [DensityGroup], 
\fBloess_span\fR as double = 0.75, 
\fBloess_degree\fR as integer = 2, 
\fBreference_sample\fR as string = "", 
\fBdensity_bandwidth\fR as double = 0, 
\fBmin_fraction\fR as double = 0.5, 
\fBobiwarp_bin_size\fR as double = 1, 
\fBobiwarp_gap_penalty\fR as double = 0.6, 
\fBobiwarp_response\fR as integer = 100, 
\fBfill_gaps\fR as boolean = TRUE, 
[\fB<Environment>\fR]);\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Do COW peak alignment and export peaktable
 
 Correlation optimized warping (COW) based on the total ion 
 current (TIC) is a widely used time alignment algorithm 
 (COW-TIC). This approach works successfully on chromatograms 
 containing few compounds and having a well-defined TIC.
.PP
.SH OPTIONS
.PP
\fBsamples\fB \fR\- 
 should be a set of samples file data, which could be extract from the \fBmz_deco\fR function.
 usaully be a list of the mzkit @\fBT:BioNovoGene.Analytical.MassSpectrometry.Math.PeakFeature\fR set list data, example as:
 
 \fBr
 list(
     sample1 = c(peak1, peak2, peak3, ...),
     sample2 = c(peak1, peak2, peak3, ...),
     ...
 );
 \fR`
. 
.PP
.PP
\fBmzdiff\fB \fR\- -. 
.PP
.PP
\fBnorm\fB \fR\- do total ion sum normalization after peak alignment and the peaktable object has been exported?. 
.PP
.PP
\fBenv\fB \fR\- -. 
.PP
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
let peaksdata = lapply(files, function(ms1) {
     mz_deco(ms1, tolerance = "da:0.01", 
         peak.width = [3,30]);
 });
 let peaktable = peak_alignment(samples = peaksdata);
 
 write.csv(peaktable, 
     file = "/path/to/peaktable.csv", 
     row.names = TRUE);
.PP
